  "prompt": "How do I build endurance for rowing? I can row about 2 km and then start failing.",
  "response": "Building endurance for rowing requires a combination of consistent training, proper technique, and attention to recovery and nutrition. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you improve your endurance and row longer distances:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Focus on Technique**\n   - **Efficiency is key**: Poor technique wastes energy and limits endurance. Work on mastering the basics of the rowing stroke (catch, drive, finish, recovery).\n   - Engage your legs, core, and arms in the correct sequence to maximize power and minimize fatigue.\n   - Consider working with a coach or watching instructional videos to refine your form.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Start with Steady-State Rowing**\n   - **Low intensity, long duration**: Row at a steady, manageable pace (60-70% of your maximum effort) for longer periods (e.g., 20-40 minutes). This builds aerobic endurance.\n   - Gradually increase your distance or time as your fitness improves.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Incorporate Interval Training**\n   - **High-intensity intervals**: Alternate between short bursts of high effort (e.g., 1 minute at 80-90% effort) and recovery (e.g., 2 minutes at an easy pace). This improves both aerobic and anaerobic capacity.\n   - Example: 5 x 500m with 2 minutes rest between intervals.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Increase Training Frequency**\n   - Row 3-5 times per week to build consistency. Mix up your workouts (e.g., steady-state, intervals, and shorter sprints) to target different energy systems.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Build Strength and Core Stability**\n   - **Strength training**: Incorporate exercises like squats, deadlifts, and pull-ups to build the muscles used in rowing.\n   - **Core exercises**: A strong core improves posture and efficiency on the rowing machine. Try planks, Russian twists, and leg raises.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Monitor Your Pace**\n   - Don\u2019t start too fast. Pacing is crucial for longer rows. Aim for a consistent split time (e.g., 2:30/500m) that you can maintain without burning out early.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Improve Your Cardio Fitness**\n   - Cross-train with activities like cycling, running, or swimming to improve overall cardiovascular endurance.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Fuel Your Body**\n   - **Hydration**: Drink plenty of water before, during, and after workouts.\n   - **Nutrition**: Eat a balanced diet with carbs for energy, protein for muscle repair, and healthy fats for sustained endurance.\n   - Consider a small snack (e.g., a banana or granola bar) before longer rowing sessions.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Prioritize Recovery**\n   - Get enough sleep to allow your body to repair and adapt.\n   - Incorporate rest days or active recovery (e.g., light stretching or walking) to prevent overtraining.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Set Goals and Track Progress**\n   - Gradually increase your distance or time (e.g., add 500m or 5 minutes to your steady-state rows each week).\n   - Use a rowing app or logbook to track your splits, distance, and improvements.\n\n---\n\n### Sample Training Plan\n   - **Monday**: 20-30 minutes steady-state rowing (moderate pace)\n   - **Wednesday**: Interval training (e.g., 5 x 500m with 2 minutes rest)\n   - **Friday**: 30-40 minutes steady-state rowing (slightly longer)\n   - **Weekend**: Strength training or cross-training (e.g., cycling or running)\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps and staying consistent, you\u2019ll gradually build the endurance needed to row longer distances without fatigue. Patience and persistence are key!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
